                <h4 class="kicker">California Drought</h4>
                <h1>Are you concerned about the drought?</h1>
            </div>
            <div class="text collapse">
                <p><span class="credits">Produced by <a href="http://www.scpr.org/about/people/staff/chris-keller">Chris Keller</a></span> | <span class="pubdate">Updated March 7, 2014</span></p>
                <p>Last month Gov. Jerry Brown <a href="http://www.scpr.org/news/2014/01/17/41647/gov-brown-proclaims-california-drought-emergency/" target="blank">declared a drought emergency in California</a> and asked state residents to voluntarily cut water usage by 20 percent.</p>
                <p>And in Northern California, some counties and cities have begun <a href="http://www.sacbee.com/2014/01/14/6071929/sacramento-council-to-weigh-water.html" target="blank">mandatory conservation measures</a> for residents. But in Southern California, most local water districts <a href="http://projects.scpr.org/static/applications/water-restrictions-by-community/" target="blank">have only asked for voluntary measures</a>.</p>
                <p>But are those realities enough to <a href="http://www.scpr.org/network/questions/water">concern you about the drought and influence your water use</a>? Click a point on the grid below and let us know how concerned you are, and how vigilant you are about water conservation.</p>
                <p>For instance, if you are concerned about the drought and taking serious steps to conserve water, you would click a point in the upper right and submit your thoughts. Likewise, if you are not concerned and your water use hasn't changed, click a point in the lower left of the grid.</p>
